36.title: Constipation
dlg:
Note that:

  1. Stool that is black may mean that the blood is coming from the upper part of the gastrointestinal (GI) tract (esophagus, stomach, and the first part of the small intestine).
  2. Bright red blood or maroon-colored stools may mean that the blood is coming from the lower part of the GI tract (large bowel, rectum, or anus).

Blood will usually look black like tar after it has passed through the intestines because it has been exposed to the body's digestive juices.

0.header:
You would consider yourself constipated if you have most of the symptoms listed below.

 

  • Have a bowel movement of less than 3 times a week.

  • Have hard stools.

  • Have difficulty passing stools.

  • Have pain while passing stools.

  • Unable to pass stool after pushing for more than 10 minutes.

  • Have a sense of incomplete evacuation after stooling.



Let's take a look at what is going on.

1.header: Did the constipation start suddenly and you also have abdominal pain?

3.header: Did it start suddenly and you also cannot pass gas or any stool?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Looking at something serious.
  • Do not take any laxative until you see a doctor.

5.header:
Is there blood coming out when you try to empty your bowel

Or in the stool?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out other causes which could be serious.
  • Even if you think it is hemorrhoids, you still need to see your doctor.

7.header:
With this constipation, are you experiencing nausea and/or vomiting?

Feeling bloated?

8.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • This may suggest serious obstruction.

Require examination and tests by the doctor such as:

  • Flat and upright abdominal x-rays
  • Water-soluble contrast enema to evaluate for colonic obstruction.
  • Barium x-ray of the small intestine
  • Possibly a CT scan
  • Sigmoidoscopy or
  • Colonoscopy.

9.header:
Are you having sharp stomach pains with this constipation?

Or a tense stomach?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • This may suggest mechanical obstruction.

11.header: Is this constipation alternating with watery diarrhea?

12.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at fecal impaction here. This is serious.
  • May also be looking at Irritable bowel syndrome

Call now if the diarrhea contains:

  • Watery mucus
  • particles of feces
  • and you have stomach cramps.

13.header: What about thin, pencil-like stools in addition to feeling constipated?

14.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bowel obstruction
  • Fecal impaction

15.header:
Have you lost weight that you didn't want to lose lately

in addition to this constipation?

16.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need complete evaluation.

17.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need complete evaluation.

20.header: Do you delay going to the bathroom when you have the urge to go?

21.header:
Yes?
You will have to stop this. This is a major cause of constipation.

This is one reason travellers always have constipation. Aside from having to sit in one place for a long time leading to lack of physical activity.

22.header: What about your diet? Is it low in fiber?

23.header:
Yes?
You will have to stop this. This is a major cause of constipation.

This is one reason travellers always have constipation. Aside from having to sit in one place for a long time leading to lack of physical activity.

24.header: What about your diet? Is it low in fiber?

26.header:
Are you currently taking any of the groups of medications listed below?

Medications that are:

  • Antihistamines
  • Antispasmodics
  • Antiparkinsonian drugs
  • Ca channel blockers
  • Opioid pain relievers
  • Antipsychotics
  • Iron, aluminum, Calcium, Bismuth?

27.header:
Yes?
These can cause constipation.

If you just started taking the medications, discuss this with your doctor.

If you are taking iron suplements, switch to the ones that will cause less constipation. The pharmacist may discuss this with you later.

28.header:
There are other causes of constipation that we did not mention.

Top among them is stress.

Let's continue and see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter to help with the constipation.

30.header: How many days has it been since your last bowel movement?

37.title: Diarrhea
dlg:
The most common cause is a viral infection of the digestive track. Bacteria and parasites can also cause diarrhea and this can be very contagious. This will usually be preceded by nausea and vomiting.

Diarrhea of any duration may cause dehydration, which means the body lacks enough fluid and electrolytes to function properly.

0.header:
You must be passing loose stools 3 or more times a day.

This can go away on its own or be a sign of a serious problem or lead to dehydration.



Before we continue, let's make sure you are not looking at a medical emergency.

1.header: In addition to this diarrhea are you also feeling faint or dizzy?

2.header:
Yes?
You have to watch out for dehydration which can be dangerous.

3.header: Are you getting more confused with things around you?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room visit.

Here is why:

  • You may be facing severe dehydration and electrolyte imbalance
  • If you are too weak, go to the nearest emergency room now.

5.header: Is your mouth feeling dry or sticky?

6.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room visit.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at severe dehydration and electrolyte imbalance.
  • If you are feeling very weak, go to the nearest emergency room now

7.header: Do you feel you are breathing abnormally?

8.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Sign of dehydration

9.header: Would you say your heart rate has increased dramatically since this diarrhea?

10.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Sign of dehydration

11.header: Are your eyes looking blood shot?

12.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possibly suffering from severe dehydration
  • Possibly suffering from electrolyte imbalance.

13.header:
Has it been more than 8 hours since the diarrhea started..

..and you have not had a urine output?

14.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Sign of a possible dehydration.

15.header:
Gently pinch and release your skin in the stomach area.

Did it flatten back to normal right away?

16.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room visit.

Here is why:

  • Possibly getting dehydrated.
  • When dehydrated, the skin does not flatten back to normal right away after being gently pinched and released.

17.header:
You just went through signs of a posssible dehydration.

If you were told to seek urgent care or emergency room visit, please do.

Dehydration can quickly result in coma, organ damage and ultimately death.

If this is not the case with you, let's take a look at the nature of the diarrhea and determine if you can ride it out or need to see a doctor as soon as possible.

20.header: Any blood in the watery stool?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria or parasites invading your bowels.
  • Tests to determine the cause of the blood in the stool is required.
  • Maroon-colored or bright red blood often mean that the blood is coming from the small or large intestine, rectum, or anal area.
  • If this keeps happening you may be looking at an inflammatory bowel disease.

22.header: Do you also have a fever above 101°F with this diarrhea?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria, viral or parasite invasion.

24.header:
Is it watery, oily and you also have stomach cramps?

Including gas?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may have bacteria or parasite related diarrhea.
  • Need antibiotics for bacteria or parasite related diarrhea.
  • OTC antidiarrhea medications may prolong the problem.

Meanwhile, drink a lot of fluids to prevent dehydration and stay away from caffeine.

26.header:
Do you have middle abdominal pain, back pain with this diarrhea?

And a high fever?

27.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Symptoms of gallbladder disease
  • Symptoms of pancreatitis

28.header:
Are you experiencing severe lower abdominal pain, cramping with this diarrhea?

And feeling bloated?

29.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room visit.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at intestinal blockage.
  • Consider this an emergency especially if the pain is severe.

30.header:
What about stomach pain or cramps...

...And you also have blood and/or mucus in the stool?

31.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Your bowels may be inflammed.
  • Possibly looking at inflammatory bowel disease or Crohn's disease.

32.header: Were you constipated before and all of a sudden you are having watery diarrhea?

33.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at fecal impaction.
  • There may be a large mass of dry hard stool trapped in the rectum.

34.header: Did you travel overseas lately?

35.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may have traveler's diarrhea caused by contaminated food or drink.
  • You will need antibiotics to deal with this.

36.header:
The nature of the diarrhea can help you make a good decision on what to do.

Let's see what we can come up with.

40.header:
Did the diarrhea start after you ate dairy products like ice cream, yogurt, cream cheese?

Or drank some milk?
Assuming they were in good condition.

41.header:
Yes?
The diarrhea may be due to lactose intolerance.

In this case, you are having problems digesting lactose (sugar found in milk products).

Know that certain types of sugar substitutes in excessive quantities can also cause diarrhea.

42.header:
Is the diarrhea watery and you have a low grade fever?

Including body ache, headache?

43.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at a stomach flu situation.

You need to prevent dehydration by drinking lots of fluid. Get plenty of rest.

If the fever is very high or the symptoms last for more than 10 days, then you will have to see a doctor.

Would you like to see the entry for stomach flu or Continue?

44.header:
Is the volume of the diarrhea large?

Very watery or fatty?
And you know it is not what you ate.

45.header:
Yes?
The problem is most likely with the small intestine.

If it continues for more than 2 days, you will have to see a doctor for this.

It could be due to your gall bladder, nerves, something speeding up movement of the intestines or even has to do with your throid hormones.

46.header:
Is this more like small but frequent stools?

Mostly with abdominal pain?

47.header:
Yes?
The problem is likely with the colons or large intestine.

If you don't know what is causing this, give the doctor a call. You may need to do colonoscopy.

Another possible cause is IBS (Irritable bowel syndrome). With IBS, the abdominal pain will be relieved after using the bathroom.

48.header:
Are you currently taking any of the medications listed below?

Such as:

  • Laxatives
  • Magnesium containing antacids
  • Antibiotics
  • Colchicine
  • Quinine/quinidine
  • Caffeine
  • Antineoplastic drugs
  • Elixirs with lactose in them.
  • SSRIs
  • Cholinesterase inhibitors (Aricept, Exelon, Razadyne, Cognex)

49.header:
Yes?
These can cause diarrhea. Discuss this with the doctor if it is severe.

50.header: Have you taken any antibiotic within the past 2 months?

51.header:
Yes?
Antibiotics can cause diarrhea even up to 2 months later.

They kill both the good and bad bacteria in the intestines. If the good ones are not replaced on time while the bad ones grew faster, this can lead to diarrhea.

Also diarrhea causing bacteria such as Clostridium difficile can grow after the use of antibiotics.

52.header:
Alright.
The goal with diarrhea is to prevent dehydration and electrolyte loss.

Signs of dehydration include:

  • Dark colored urine
  • Thirst
  • Dry or sticky mouth
  • Dry skin
  • Feeling dizzy or lightheaded
  • Low or no urine output
  • Sunken eyes

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend for diarrhea that is available over the counter.

But before that just one more question.

60.header: How many times have you been to the bathroom since it all started?

61.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}} times

Not too bad so far.

If you don't think you need to seek urgent care from the discussions so far, the goal will be to prevent dehydration.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend for this or would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

62.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}} times

Getting bad?

If you don't think you need to seek urgent care from the discussions so far, the goal will be to prevent dehydration and let it run its course.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend for this or would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

63.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}} times

Bad?

If you don't think you need to seek urgent care from the discussions so far, the goal will be to prevent dehydration and let it run its course.

If you think you are dehydrated, seek urgent care.

If for some reason you cannot seek urgent care, let's see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter to help prevent further dehydration.

0.header:
Let's see what to use for nausea and or vomiting over-the-counter.

Many things can cause nausea. Viral infection such as stomach flu, gallstones, motion sickness, pregnancy or even fear and anxiety to name a few.



Let's determine the best course of action to take with this nausea and vomiting.

1.header: With this nausea and or vomiting do you have any fever (may be low-grade) and or chills?

2.header:
Nausea with fever, may indicate something serious going on.

Let's navigate this carefully and decide if you need to seek urgent care or if you can ride this out.

4.header: In addition to this nausea and fever, do you also have diarrhea?

5.header:
Yes?
May be looking at the stomach flu or food poisoning.

Let's see if that is what you are probably looking at.

6.header:
Anybody else with the same symptoms, but you did not eat the same food?

In other words do you know if there is a bug going around?

7.header:
Yes?
Probably looking at stomach flu. (viral gastroenteritis)

Stomach flu starts when you:

  • come in contact with an infected person,
  • were exposed to an infected person through poor sanitation
  • or you ate or drank a contaminated food or water.

Would you like to see the entry for stomach flu or Continue?

8.header: Anybody else has the same symptoms and you ate the same food?

9.header:
Yes?
Probably looking at food poisoning.

Suspect food poisoning if someone else is sick after you ate the same food and it all started at once.

If you and someone else have the same symptoms but did not eat the same food lately, suspect the stomach flu.

Would you like to see our entry for food poisoning or Continue?

10.header: Do you also have a headache with all these?

11.header:
Alright.
See the entry for food poisoning or stomach flu if you are suspecting any of them.

Would you like to Continue or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

12.header:
Was this a nagging headache before the nausea / vomiting and diarrhea started?

Or after the nausea and vomiting?

13.header:
Before?
If it is before, probably looking at food poisoning.

Often times, food poisoning start with you feeling a nagging headache, then fever, feeling tired, before you start throwing up with diarrhea and the rest.

Would you like to see our entry on food poisoning or Continue to see other situations associated with nausea and or vomiting?

14.header:
After?
Suspect food poisoning if a nagging headache before the nausea and vomiting.

If it is after and you know someone else has the same symptoms and you did not eat the same food or you might have come in contact with some one with the stomach bug, then it is probably a stomach flu.

Would you like to see the entry for stomach flu or Continue to check out the other situations that involve nausea and or vomiting with fever?

20.header:
Are you feeling a sharp pain in your lower right or middle abdomen?

With this nausea, vomiting, fever?

21.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at appendicitis.

22.header:
Was this a dull aching pain that moved from your navel to the right lower part of you stomach?

And grew sharper with time?

23.header:
Yes?
This can be a sign of appendicitis.

Let's make sure you are not looking at one and if so do the right thing.

24.header:
Press on the area of the pain and release the pressure.

Does the pain get sharper?

26.header: Does the pain get worse when you cough or walk and you prefer to lie still?

27.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • This is a sign of appendicitis.

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

28.header:
Are you shaking with this pain, nausea and/or vomiting?

With chills?

29.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible signs of appendicitis.

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

30.header:
Those were possible signs of appendicitis.

You should seek emergency room visit if most applied to you.

Know that if your appendix ruptures, you may feel less pain for a short time and even feel better.

But, the lining of the abdomen will get swollen and infected (peritonitis) and then the pain will get worse and you will become very sick.

If you don't think you are looking at appendicitis, let's continue and find out what else may be causing this nausea and vomiting.

40.header: With this nausea and fever do you also have upper right or middle abdominal pain?

41.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at gallstones attack.

42.header:
Is this like a dull, constant pain?

May also be sharp and cramping.

43.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of a gallstone attack going on.

44.header:
Does this pain spread to below the right shoulder blade?

Or your back?

45.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of gallstone attack.

You will need to seek emergency room visit or at a minimum urgent care if this apply to you. Would you like to do that or Continue?

46.header:
Is your skin turning yellow?

Or are you passing clay-colored stools?

47.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Sign of gallstone attack.

48.header:
Those were signs of a gallstone attack.

If this apply to you, seek emergency room visit. If not, let's see what else may be causing this nausea and or vomiting with fever.

50.header: Do you also have a stiff neck along with this nausea and fever?

51.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at meningitis which can be a life threatening emergency.

52.header: Do you have a severe headache with this stiff neck and nausea?

53.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • This is a sign of meningitis.

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

54.header: Are you more sensitive to light with this stiff neck and nausea with fever?

55.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible sign of meningitis.

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

56.header: Do you feel you are breathing rapidly with this stiff neck, nausea and fever?

57.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible sign of meningitis

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

58.header:
We just went through the main signs of meningitis.

Bacteria meningitis is a medical emergency.

Urgent treatment is required to avoid serious complications and even death. Time is of a factor.

If you don't think it is meningitis you are looking at, let's continue and see what else may be causing this nausea and or vomiting.

60.header:
If you have nausea with fever, chances are something serious is going on.

We will recommend you visit the nearest urgent care clinic.

If any of the discussions does not apply to you, then let's continue.

61.header: How many times have you thrown up since it all started?

62.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

Less than 3 times?

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help with the nausea and vomiting.

This will assume that:

  • No other symptoms are present or nausea and or vomiting is the predominant symptom.

  • You know what is causing the nausea and vomiting.

  • You want to know what is available for nausea and or vomiting over the counter.

63.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

More than 3 times?

Watch out for the signs and symptoms of dehydration.

Seek urgent care if other symptoms are present.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help with the nausea and vomiting.

64.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

Pretty bad?

Have to seek urgent care or give the doctor a call.

Call the doctor or the after hours line. They can always call in a prescription to take care of this nausea and/or vomiting for you. You don't have to wait till the office is opened for business.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help with the nausea and vomiting at least until you see a doctor.

70.header: Do you also have diarrhea with this nausea or vomiting?

71.header:
You said:{{currentTemp}}

Pretty bad?

Have to seek urgent care or give the doctor a call.

Call the doctor or the after hours line. They can always call in a prescription to take care of this nausea and/or vomiting for you. You don't have to wait till the office is opened for business.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter to help with the nausea and vomiting at least until you see a doctor.

72.header: Do you have burning pain in the stomach with this nausea and or vomiting?

73.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at peptic ulcer or gastritis
  • If you have a history of ulcer, it is a good time to check with your doctor.

74.header:
What about burning pain in the lower part of the chest?

With a sour or bitter taste in the mouth or throat.

75.header:
Yes?
Most likely looking at a serious case of heartburn or GERD.

76.header:
Are you in addition to the nausea and/or vomiting feeling dizzy?

With these symptoms:

  • Sweating
  • Drooling saliva
  • Feeling cold
  • Headaches
  • Pale skin
  • Fatigue

And you are in a motion situation like a moving boat, train, airplane, car, or amusement park rides?

77.header:
Yes?
Most likely looking at a serious case of heartburn or GERD.

78.header:
Do you have a severe headache with this nausea/vomiting?

Especially with:

  • Sensitivity to light
  • Sensitivity to sounds
  • Sensitivity to smells
  • Blurred vision
  • Headache that has a pulsating, throbbing feel to it
  • Lightheadedness.

79.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at a migraine

80.header: Are you of child bearing age and if so did you miss a period?

81.header:
Yes?
Take a pregnancy test especially if it is triggered by food.

Nausea or vomiting due to pregnancy often occur in the morning or can be triggered by food.

82.header: Are you diabetic?

83.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible ketoacidosis

84.header: Did you just start taking a new medication?

85.header:
Yes?
Most medications will cause nausea and/or vomiting.

Some medications may also cause nausea or vomiting days after you started taking them. Even Acetaminophen.

86.header:
There are other causes of vomiting not talked about here.

For instance, you can trigger the vomiting center as a result of being stressed out.

Eating some mushrooms can cause vomiting many days later.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend you use over-the-counter.

39.title: Stomach Ache
dlg:
Symptoms may start with:

  • pain around your belly button.
  • pain may be minor at first, but it becomes more sharp and severe.
  • your appetite will be reduced
  • you may have nausea or vomiting
  • you may have low grade fever.

As the swelling in the appendix increases, in 12 to 24 hours after the start of the illness:

  • Pain tends to move into your right lower abdomen
  • Focuses right above the appendix at a place called McBurney's point.
  • Pain will increase when you gently press on your lower right belly area.

If your appendix ruptures:

  • You may have less pain for a short time and feel better.
  • However, the lining of your abdomen can become infected and swollen from the rupture (peritonitis).
  • Then the pain gets worse and you become very sick.
  • Your pain may be worse when you walk or cough.
  • Sudden movement causes pain.
  • You may prefer to lie still because any movement gives you pain.
  • You might have nausea and vomiting
  • You might be shaking and feverish
  • You might have chills with diarrhea

If you are nodding your head to any of these, this is a
medical emergency
and you need to get to the hospital now.

Severe pain that:

  • started suddenly and may go away suddenly
  • comes in waves (colicky)
  • is felt in the belly area or side of the back
  • may move to groin area (groin pain) or testicles (testicle pain)

Also severe pain with

  • Blood in urine
  • Abnormal urine color
  • nausea and vomiting
  • chills or fever

0.header:
Let's figure out what is going on with the stomach and make a good decision.

You will narrow down the cause and determine if you need urgent care or if it is something that can be taken care of at the local pharmacy with over-the-counter remedies.

1.header:
Good to have an idea of what you are dealing with.

Know that:
The severity of the stomach pain may not reflect the magnitude of the problem causing the pain. For instance pain caused by appendicitis is usually dull in the beginning.

2.header:
With this stomach pain, are you seeing blood in the stool?

Or vomiting blood?

3.header:
Good to have an idea of what you are dealing with.

Know that:
The severity of the stomach pain may not reflect the magnitude of the problem causing the pain. For instance pain caused by appendicitis is usually dull in the beginning.

4.header:
With this stomach pain, are you seeing blood in the stool?

Or vomiting blood?

6.header:
Any shoulder pain?

Or pain in or between shoulder blades?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Heart attack warning.
  • Need to rule this out unless it is pain you are familiar with.

8.header: If a female, are you pregnant or think you could be pregnant?

9.header:
Seek a doctor or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out a serious cause if pregnant.
  • Need to rule out pregnancy if not pregnant.

10.header: Are you having difficulty breathing with this stomach ache?

11.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Consider this an urgent medical situation.

Note:
You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

12.header: Are you currently being treated for cancer?

13.header:
Seek emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Serious situation going on.

14.header:
Did this stomach pain start suddenly?

And is sharp?

15.header:
Seek urgent care or the emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible emergency situation.

16.header:
You've been trying to rule out going to the emergency room.

But wait!
You are not out of the woods yet.

Let's make sure it is not something like kidney stones, appendicitis, or even food poisoning.

20.header: Is the pain confined to the lower right belly area?

30.header:
Yes?
Let's make sure you are not looking at appendicitis.

31.header: Did this stomach pain start around the belly button?

33.header: Was this pain minor at first, but became sharper and severe?

34.header:
Yes?
Appendicitis usually start this way. But don't panic yet.

Appendicitis usually start with:

  • Pain around the belly button
  • Pain, minor at first, but becomes sharp and severe.

35.header: Are you feeling nauseated and/or vomiting?

36.header:
Yes?
There is a feeling of nausea or vomiting with appendicitis.

Symptoms include:

  • Pain around the belly button
  • Pain, minor at first, but becomes sharp and severe.
  • Nausea and / or vomiting

37.header: Do you have any appetite for food?

38.header:
No appetite?
With appendicitis, there is reduced appetite for food.

Symptoms include:

  • Pain around the belly button
  • Pain, minor at first, but becomes sharp and severe.
  • Nausea and/or vomiting
  • Reduced appetite.

39.header: Are you experiencing low grade fever?

40.header:
Yes?
This can be a symptom of appendicitis.

Symptoms include:

  • Pain around the belly button
  • Pain, minor at first, but becomes sharp and severe.
  • Nausea and/or vomiting
  • Reduced appetite.
  • Low grade fever

41.header:
Gently press on the right lower belly area.

Does the pain increase?

42.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of inflammation of the appendix.

Pressing on the right lower belly area increases the pain.

43.header: Does this pain get worse when you walk?

45.header: Does the stomach pain get worse when you cough?

46.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of appendicitis. The stomach pain is worse when you cough or walk.

47.header:
Those were signs and symptoms of appendicitis.

Appendicitis is swelling or inflammation of the appendix caused by infection or fecal matter blockade.

The appendix is a small pouch attached to the beginning of your large intestine.

Tap on the "FYI" button to see a description of the symptoms.

Continue if it is not what you are looking at.

50.header: Is the stomach pain in the right or middle upper belly area?

51.header:
Yes?
let's make sure you are not looking at a gallstone situation.

52.header:
If the pain is in the right or middle upper belly..

..is it dull and constant?

54.header: Is it sharp and cramping?

55.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a gallstone attack. But don't panic yet.

Symptoms include:

  • Dull, constant pain in the right upper or middle upper abdomen
  • Sharp, cramping pain in the right upper or middle upper abdomen

56.header: Is this pain spreading or did it spread to your back?

58.header: Did it spread to below the right shoulder blade?

59.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of gallstones attack.

Symptoms include:

  • Dull, constant pain in the right upper or middle upper abdomen
  • Sharp, cramping pain in the right upper or middle upper abdomen
  • Pain that may spread to the back or below the right shoulder blade

60.header: Are you passing clay-colored stools

61.header:
You are?
With gallstones, you may pass clay-colored stools.

Symptoms of gallstones include:

  • Dull, constant pain in the right upper or middle upper abdomen
  • Sharp, cramping pain in the right upper or middle upper abdomen
  • Pain that may spread to the back or below the right shoulder blade.
  • Clay colored stools

62.header: Is your skin or whites of your eyes yellowing (jaundice)?

63.header:
Yes?
With gallstones, the skin or whites of the eyes may be yellowing.

64.header: Any fever with this pain?

66.header: What about nausea or vomiting?

68.header:
Those were signs of gallstones attack.

If you nodded your head to the discussion so far, you should go to the nearest hospital or urgent care clinic?

If that is not the case, we can keep looking into what may be causing this stomach pain you are experiencing.

70.header:
Did this pain start on the belly area or side of the back?

And moved down to the groin or bladder area?

71.header:
Yes?
Hmmm. Let's make sure you are not looking at kidney stones.

72.header:
Is this a severe pain that started suddenly?

It may also go away suddenly only to return later.

73.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of kidney stones. But don't panic yet.

74.header: Any blood in the urine?

76.header:
What about an abnormal urine color?

Or cloudy urine with strong odor?

77.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of kidney stones.

Symptoms include:

  • Severe pain that started suddenly
  • Pain that comes in waves (colicky)
  • Pain that moved down to the groin or bladder area
  • Bloody urine
  • Cloudy urine with strong odor

78.header: Are you experiencing nausea and or vomiting?

79.header:
Yes?
You may experience this with kidney stones.

Symptoms include:

  • Severe pain that started suddenly
  • Pain that comes in waves (colicky)
  • Pain that moved down to the groin or bladder area
  • Bloody urine
  • Cloudy urine with strong odor
  • Nausea and vomiting

80.header: What about frequent urge to urinate with this severe stomach pain?

81.header:
Yes?
Possible kidney stones.
If with severe stomach pain.

kidney stones symptoms include:

  • Severe pain that started suddenly
  • Pain that comes in waves (colicky)
  • Pain that moved down to the groin or bladder area
  • Bloody urine
  • Cloudy urine with strong odor
  • Nausea and vomiting
  • Frequent urge to urinate

82.header:
Fever and chills.
Any of that?

83.header:
Yes?
Passing kidney stones can aslo cause this.

kidney stones symptoms include:

  • Severe pain that started suddenly
  • Pain that comes in waves (colicky)
  • Pain that moved down to the groin or bladder area
  • Bloody urine
  • Cloudy urine with strong odor
  • Nausea and vomiting
  • Frequent urge to urinate
  • Fever and chills

84.header:
Those were symptoms of kidney stones pain.

Main signs your stomach pain might be due to kidney stones are listed in the "FYI" below.

If these apply to you, we suggest you go to the nearest hospital or urgent care clinic.

Would you like to do that now or continue if you don't think it is a kidney stone situation?

90.header: Do you feel pain mainly when you apply pressure to certain parts of the belly?

91.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Doctors call this point tenderness. It means you have tenderness in a certain area.
  • May be looking at peritonitis (inflammation of the tissue that lines the abdominal cavity)
  • May be looking at appendicitis or twisted Fallopian tube.
  • May be looking at certain types of hernia.

If you or someone else touch parts of the belly and you feel pain in that part or the area feels tender, we consider this a medical emergency.

92.header: Would you describe the stomach pain as being cramp-like?

93.header:
Yes?
This is more likely due to gas and bloating.

If it is followed by diarrhea, then it is due to gas or bloating. You may be suffering from lactose intolerance or food allergies.

If it lasts more than 24 hours or there is fever, then you will need to seek urgent care.

94.header:
Do you feel the stomach ache all over your belly?

Or in more than half of your belly?

95.header:
Yes?
You may be looking at a stomach virus, indigestion, or gas.

If it gets more severe, your intestines might be blocked.

96.header:
Is this pain dull and coming in waves?

And you are vomiting?

97.header:
Yes?
May be looking at intestinal obstruction.

98.header:
Is this stomach ache sharp and constant?

Worse when you move?

99.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at peritonitis.

  • If you feel relief when lying still and severe pain when you move or try to get up. Call 911.

100.header: Did the pain start suddenly, like turning on the light switch?

101.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible causes include kidney stones, perforated ulcer.

  • Something may have ruptured in the stomach.

  • If you are pregnant, you might be looking at a ruptured ectopic pregnancy.

102.header: Does this pain travel to any other areas of the body?

103.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

If it travels to:

  • Right collar bone:
    May suggest gallbladder pain

  • Left shoulder area:
    May suggest a ruptured spleen or even pancreatitis.

  • Private parts:
    May suggest Kidney stones.

  • The back:
    Must seek emergency help.

104.header:
There are other causes of stomach pain not discussed so far.

Some will require emergency care, others urgent care while others are due to minor stomach discomfort.

Bottom line:
If you are writhing around with severe pain trying to find the best comfortable position for you, you should start heading to the emergency room or seek urgent care.

Especially if it started suddenly and you know you didn't eat anything bad or do not have gas problems.

If you are convinced your stomach pain is not life threatening or does not require urgent care, let's see what a pharmacist recommend you take to relieve the pain that is available over-the-counter.
